VPNs act like proxies, routing your internet traffic through their servers to hide your location. However, they can see and record all your data because it passes through them. If a VPN provider is untrustworthy or compromised, your information can be exposed. VPNs don’t encrypt messages end-to-end, so they aren’t foolproof privacy tools. For real security, stronger methods like end-to-end encryption are needed. Look into “VPN risks,” “proxy servers,” and “end-to-end encryption” for deeper understanding.
Many VPN apps in app stores are controlled or funded by governments.
This includes popular “free” apps that quietly log traffic and inject tracking.